    <patterns>
      <pattern name="AIFunctionFactory.Create tool wiring (canonical reference)" location="src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/Chat/Tools/AnalysisExecutionTools.cs">
        Tool class is a `public sealed class` constructed inside
        `SprkChatAgentFactory.ResolveTools` (NOT registered in DI per ADR-010 + AIPL-053).
        Exposes a `public IEnumerable&lt;AIFunction&gt; GetTools()` method that yields
        `AIFunctionFactory.Create(methodReference, name: "ToolName", description: "...")`
        per tool method. The `[Description("...")]` attribute on the method + parameters is
        load-bearing for LLM tool-schema generation. Mirror this exactly for
        `InvokeSummarizePlaybookTool`.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Capability-gated tool resolution block" location="src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/Chat/SprkChatAgentFactory.cs (lines 807–834 for AnalysisExecutionTools)">
        Tool instantiation lives inside `ResolveTools` wrapped in `try/catch` with
        `attempted++ / resolved++ / failedTools.Add(...)` bookkeeping per AIPU2-063
        per-tool error isolation. Gate behind a playbook capability (e.g.,
        `capabilities.Contains(PlaybookCapabilities.SummarizeSession)` or reuse the
        appropriate existing capability). The factory resolves required services
        (orchestrator, chat client, citation context) from `scopedProvider`. SessionId +
        tenant + ChatSession.UploadedFiles flow in via constructor args from the factory's
        existing `ChatHostContext` / scoped state.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Orchestrator delegate (avoids handler→orchestrator cycle)" location="src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/Insights/AssistantToolCallHandler.cs lines 132–222">
        The tool can either (a) take a direct `SessionSummarizeOrchestrator` constructor
        dependency, OR (b) take a `Func&lt;...&gt;` delegate over the orchestrator's shared
        internal method to avoid constructor cycles. Use direct dependency since the
        orchestrator from task 012 is a concrete class with no circular dependency on the
        tool. Mirror the AssistantToolCallHandler delegate pattern only if a cycle
        emerges during implementation.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="AIPU2-061 CapabilityRouter per-turn tool-injection" location="src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/Capabilities/CapabilityRouter.cs">
        The Layer 1 keyword classifier + Layer 2 LLM classifier select a subset of
        tools per turn based on the user's message and the playbook capabilities. The
        capability manifest entries' `ToolNames` lists determine which tools are
        discoverable by the router. Register the new tool's name in the appropriate
        playbook capability's `ToolNames` allow-list (or under a new capability key
        if the existing taxonomy lacks a fit — preferred to reuse an existing capability).
        Verify the router selects the new tool for natural-language Summarize prompts
        via the existing `ICapabilityRouter.RouteAsync` integration test.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Two-path convergence (endpoint + tool → same orchestrator method)" location="src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/Insights/InsightsOrchestrator.cs">
        The Insights `/ask` endpoint and the `insights.query` chat-agent tool both call
        into the same orchestrator method. R5 mirrors this discipline: task 014
        (`POST /api/ai/chat/sessions/{id}/summarize`) and task 015 (this tool) both call
        `SessionSummarizeOrchestrator.SummarizeAsync(...)`. Add an equivalence unit test
        per the FR-05 convergence requirement.
      </pattern>
    </patterns>
  </knowledge>

  <context>
    <background>
      R5 ships a chat-driven "Summarize a Document" vertical slice. Users upload up to 20
      files to a chat session; both a direct endpoint (task 014) and a chat-agent
      tool-call (this task) trigger Summarize. The LLM tool-calls this function when the
      user types a natural-language Summarize request ("summarize the attached docs",
      "TL;DR these files in bullet style") — this is the FR-03 prompt-first path
      counterpart to the FR-08 UI-driven "Summarize this only" button (task 021).

      Tool-routing disambiguation between this tool and the upcoming `insights.query`
      tool (task 024) is a known UR-01 risk; the mitigation is tool-description-quality
      discipline (spec NFR-12 + plan.md High-Risk Items table). The description must
      semantically scope routing — "summarize files uploaded to the chat session" vs
      "answer analytical questions about a matter/project/invoice entity" — so the LLM
      Layer 2 classifier picks the right tool for each natural-language prompt.

      This task adds NO new top-level `Program.cs` lines (registers inside
      `SprkChatAgentFactory.ResolveTools` per the AIPL-053 / AnalysisExecutionTools
      precedent), NO new feature flags (kill-switch inherits via
      `NullSprkChatAgentFactory`), and NO new chat-agent or tool framework.
    </background>
