                 task-execute decision tree.
      📖 PROTOCOL STEPS TO EXECUTE: Steps 0–10 with Step 9.5 quality gates.
      Proceeding with Step 0...
      ```
    </step>
    <step order="1" name="Review Progress">
      Read `tasks/TASK-INDEX.md`. Confirm task 015 status is 🔲, dependency 012 is ✅,
      parallel-safe = true (P2-G3). Read `current-task.md` to verify no R5 task is in
      flight conflicting with this site. Confirm tasks 005, 006 are ✅ (orchestrator's
      streaming infrastructure dependencies). Confirm task 014 is in flight or queued
      (sibling — convergence target).
    </step>
    <step order="2" name="Gather Resources">
      Read every file in &lt;inputs&gt; and &lt;knowledge&gt;. Specifically:
      (a) Read `SprkChatAgentFactory.ResolveTools` (lines 540–1040) to internalize the
          tool-registration block pattern + AIPU2-063 error-isolation discipline.
      (b) Read `AnalysisExecutionTools.cs` (canonical tool-class shape) and
          `AnalysisQueryTools.cs` (canonical pattern when constructor takes a service).
      (c) Read task 012's POML to confirm the exact `SessionSummarizeOrchestrator`
          signature + the shared internal method name + return type.
      (d) Read ADR-013, ADR-010, ADR-018 in full.
      (e) Read `bff-extensions.md` §F (test obligation) + §F.1 (asymmetric-registration
          anti-pattern) — verify unconditional registration discipline.
      (f) Read `CapabilityRouter.cs` lines 1–200 to understand the keyword + LLM
          classification flow and how `ToolNames` allow-lists drive per-turn selection.
    </step>
    <step order="3" name="Plan Implementation + Tool Description Authoring (NFR-12)">
      Author the tool-class skeleton + the tool description text. The description text
      is the single most load-bearing artifact of this task per NFR-12. Draft two
      candidate descriptions and pick one explicitly:

      Candidate A (concise):
      "Summarize one or more files uploaded to the current chat session using the
      Summarize playbook. Use when the user asks to summarize attached documents,
      session files, or 'these files'. Do NOT use for analytical questions about a
      matter/project/invoice entity (use insights.query for that)."

      Candidate B (parameter-aware):
      "Produce a Summarize playbook output over files uploaded to this chat session.
      Accepts an optional list of fileIds (defaults to ALL session-uploaded files) and
      an optional style ('bullet', 'paragraph', 'tldr'; defaults to the playbook
      default). Returns a streamed structured summary with TL;DR + per-file highlights.
      Use for chat-session file summarization only — not for matter/project/invoice
      entity Q&amp;A."

      Pick ONE explicitly + record the decision in task notes. The description MUST
      explicitly differentiate from `insights.query` (NFR-12 mitigation of UR-01 risk).
      Author parameter-level `[Description(...)]` attributes for both `fileIds` and
      `style` so the LLM tool-schema is unambiguous.

      Also: identify the playbook capability under which to gate the tool (read
      `PlaybookCapabilities` constants in the existing factory; reuse if a fit exists,
      otherwise add a new constant + capability manifest row — prefer reuse). Decide
      whether to wire via direct `SessionSummarizeOrchestrator` constructor argument or
      via a `Func&lt;...&gt;` delegate (default: direct — no cycle expected).
    </step>
    <step order="4" name="Create `InvokeSummarizePlaybookTool` class">
      Create `src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/Chat/Tools/InvokeSummarizePlaybookTool.cs`
      following the canonical `AnalysisExecutionTools` shape:
      - `public sealed class InvokeSummarizePlaybookTool`
      - Constructor: takes `SessionSummarizeOrchestrator` (from task 012),
        `ChatSession` / sessionId / tenantId (from factory's existing scoped state),
        `Func&lt;ChatSseEvent, CancellationToken, Task&gt;? sseWriter`, optional `HttpContext`
        for OBO context propagation per ADR-028 (no token snapshot — pass through).
      - Method: `public async Task&lt;string&gt; InvokeSummarizePlaybookAsync(string[]? fileIds, string? style, CancellationToken ct)`
        decorated with `[Description("...")]` from Step 3.
      - Parameter attributes: `[Description("...")]` on each parameter.
      - Implementation: validates fileIds against the active `ChatSession.UploadedFiles[]`
        manifest (task 004); defaults to all files when null/empty; defaults style to
        the playbook default when null/whitespace; calls
        `_orchestrator.SummarizeAsync(sessionId, tenantId, fileIds, style, sseWriter, ct)`
        (exact signature per task 012 — adjust if it differs); returns the orchestrator's
        return string (e.g., final TL;DR text for the agent's conversation context).
      - `public IEnumerable&lt;AIFunction&gt; GetTools()` yielding `AIFunctionFactory.Create(
        InvokeSummarizePlaybookAsync, name: "InvokeSummarizePlaybook", description: "...")`.
      Mirror the XML doc-comment density of `AnalysisExecutionTools.cs`.
    </step>
    <step order="5" name="Wire tool into `SprkChatAgentFactory.ResolveTools`">
      Extend `SprkChatAgentFactory.ResolveTools` with a new capability-gated block,
      placed alongside the existing AnalysisExecutionTools block (around lines 807–834).
      Pattern (mirror existing tool-resolution blocks exactly):

      ```csharp
      // --- InvokeSummarizePlaybookTool (R5 D2-05) ---
      // Gated behind the [chosen capability] capability.
      // Requires SessionSummarizeOrchestrator (task 012) + active ChatSession.
      if (capabilities.Contains(PlaybookCapabilities.SummarizeSession) && /* orchestrator available */)
      {
          attempted++;
          try
          {
              var orchestrator = scopedProvider.GetRequiredService&lt;SessionSummarizeOrchestrator&gt;();
              var invokeSummarize = new InvokeSummarizePlaybookTool(
                  orchestrator,
                  sessionId, tenantId,
                  sseWriter,
                  httpContext);
              tools.AddRange(invokeSummarize.GetTools());
              resolved++;
          }
          catch (Exception ex)
          {
              _logger.LogWarning(ex, "Failed to resolve InvokeSummarizePlaybookTool — skipping");
              failedTools.Add(nameof(InvokeSummarizePlaybookTool));
          }
      }
      ```

      No new DI registration required if the orchestrator is already registered by task
      012 inside `AnalysisServicesModule.cs`. Confirm. If a new capability constant is
      needed, add it inside `PlaybookCapabilities` static class (existing file in the
      Chat namespace). ZERO new `Program.cs` lines per ADR-010.
    </step>
    <step order="6" name="Update capability manifest + `ToolNames` allow-list (AIPU2-061)">
      Update the appropriate capability manifest entry (or capability constants file) so
      `InvokeSummarizePlaybook` appears in `ToolNames` for the chosen capability. This
      makes the tool discoverable by `CapabilityRouter.RouteAsync` and selectable for
      per-turn injection when the user's prompt classifies as Summarize intent. Verify
      via the `CapabilityValidator` flow (per AIPU2-061 line 1088+ in SprkChatAgentFactory).
    </step>
    <step order="7" name="Authored convergence test (FR-05)">
      Add a unit test in `tests/unit/Sprk.Bff.Api.Tests/Services/Ai/Chat/Tools/` named
      `InvokeSummarizePlaybookToolTests.cs`:
      - Test 1 (delegation): `InvokeSummarizePlaybookAsync(null, null, ct)` calls
        `SessionSummarizeOrchestrator.SummarizeAsync(...)` exactly once with all
        session-file IDs + default style; asserts via mocked orchestrator + Moq/NSubstitute.
      - Test 2 (fileIds defaulting): pass `fileIds: new[] { "abc", "xyz" }`; orchestrator
        is called with that explicit list (no defaulting). Pass `fileIds: []`;
        orchestrator is called with the full session manifest.
      - Test 3 (style defaulting): `style: null` → orchestrator called with default
        playbook style; `style: "bullet"` → orchestrator called with "bullet".
      - Test 4 (convergence/FR-05): record SSE events emitted via the `sseWriter`
        delegate for an identical input. Run the same input through the direct
        endpoint's call path (from task 014 — invoke the same orchestrator method
        directly) and assert the produced `FieldDelta` SSE event stream is IDENTICAL
        in content + ordering. This is the load-bearing FR-05 convergence proof.
      - Test 5 (validation): unknown `fileIds` (not in `ChatSession.UploadedFiles[]`)
        produces a clear error or skips invalid entries — confirm with task 012's
        orchestrator contract.

      Add a routing test in `tests/unit/Sprk.Bff.Api.Tests/Services/Ai/Chat/SprkChatAgentFactoryTests.cs`
      (or a new file) asserting: when `capabilities` contains the gating capability,
      `InvokeSummarizePlaybook` appears in the resolved `IReadOnlyList&lt;AIFunction&gt;`;
      when absent, it does NOT appear; when `routingResult` filters tools to a different
      capability, this tool is excluded per AIPU2-061.
    </step>
    <step order="8" name="LLM tool-call routing smoke test">
      With a running BFF (locally or on Spaarke Dev), exercise the chat-agent with a set
      of natural-language Summarize prompts and verify the LLM tool-calls
      `InvokeSummarizePlaybook` (not e.g. `SearchDocuments` or `RefineText`):
      - "summarize the attached document"
      - "give me a TL;DR of the files I uploaded"
      - "summarize these documents in bullet style"
      - "what's the gist of the attached PDFs?"
      Also negative tests (must NOT select `InvokeSummarizePlaybook`):
      - "what's the total spend on matter X?" → should select `insights.query` once
        task 024 lands; for this task's verification stage `insights.query` may not yet
        be registered — verify the prompt does NOT spuriously trigger
        `InvokeSummarizePlaybook` when no session files are uploaded.

      Capture the tool-call traces (Activity span or log lines) and record them in task
      notes. If routing is incorrect, refine the description text (Step 3) and re-run.
      Repeat until at least 3 of 4 positive prompts route correctly + the negative
      prompts do NOT trigger this tool.
    </step>
    <step order="9" name="Verify acceptance criteria">
      Walk every &lt;acceptance-criterion&gt; below; record evidence per criterion in task
      notes (`notes/task-015-evidence.md`): tool visible in agent's resolved tool
      catalog (factory log line + AIFunction list assertion); LLM correctly tool-calls
      for ≥3 of 4 natural-language test prompts; convergence test passes (identical
      `FieldDelta` SSE streams); middleware stack inherited (telemetry events present,
      cost-control middleware engaged); tool description scopes routing per NFR-12
      (negative prompts do NOT trigger this tool); publish-size measurement recorded.
    </step>
    <step order="9.5" name="Quality Gates (FULL rigor)">
      Run `code-review` skill against the new tool class + the
      `SprkChatAgentFactory.ResolveTools` extension + the test file. Run `adr-check`
      skill against the same; verify ADR-013 (BFF-only AI; agent via factory; middleware
      inherited), ADR-010 (DI minimalism — zero new top-level lines), ADR-018 (no new
      feature flag — kill-switch inherits via NullSprkChatAgentFactory), ADR-014 (tenant
      isolation flows via orchestrator delegate), ADR-028 (no token snapshot — OBO
      passes through). Both gates MUST pass before marking task complete.

      Run BFF publish + size check:
      `dotnet publish -c Release src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/ -o deploy/api-publish/`
      Measure compressed output; record absolute size + delta vs prior baseline (per R5
      CLAUDE.md §3.6). Expected delta is small (one new class + one tool-resolution
      block) — target +0.0–0.1 MB.

      Verify no new HIGH-severity CVE: `dotnet list package --vulnerable --include-transitive`.
    </step>
    <step order="10" name="Document + Complete">
      Update task POML status to `complete`. Update `TASK-INDEX.md`: 015 🔲 → ✅. Reset
